y writers to provide a uniform opt-out mechanism for new functionality for their users."},{"content":"It establishes a loosely-coupled contract between components in order to communicate an opt-out request.","pos":[74048,74152]},{"content":"This capability is typically important when a change is made to existing functionality.","pos":[74153,74240]},{"content":"Conversely, there is already an implicit opt-in for new functionality.","pos":[74241,74311]},{"content":"With <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.AppContext&gt;</ph>, libraries define and expose compatibility switches, while code that depends on them can set those switches to affect the library behavior.","pos":[74322,74491],"source":"With <xref:System.AppContext>, libraries define and expose compatibility switches, while code that depends on them can set those switches to affect the library behavior."},{"content":"By default, libraries provide the new functionality, and they only alter it (that is, they provide the previous functionality) if the switch is set.","pos":[74492,74640]},{"content":"An application (or a library) can declare the value of a switch (which is always a <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Boolean&gt;</ph> value) that a dependent library defines.","pos":[74651,74796],"source":"An application (or a library) can declare the value of a switch (which is always a <xref:System.Boolean> value) that a dependent library defines."},{"content":"The switch is always implicitly <ph id=\"ph1\">`false`</ph>.","pos":[74797,74837],"source":" The switch is always implicitly `false`."},{"content":"Setting the switch to <ph id=\"ph1\">`true`</ph> enables it.","pos":[74838,74878],"source":" Setting the switch to `true` enables it."},{"content":"Explicitly setting the switch to <ph id=\"ph1\">`false`</ph> provides the new behavior.","pos":[74879,74946],"source":" Explicitly setting the switch to `false` provides the new behavior."},{"content":"The library must check if a consumer has declared the value of the switch and then appropriately act on it.","pos":[75062,75169]},{"content":"It's beneficial to use a consistent format for switches, since they are a formal contract exposed by a library.","pos":[75886,75997]},{"content":"The following are two obvious formats.","pos":[75998,76036]},{"pos":[76048,76081],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Switch<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.<bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>namespace<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept>.<bpt id=\"p3\">*</bpt>switchname<ept id=\"p3\">*</ept>","source":"*Switch*.*namespace*.*switchname*"},{"pos":[76093,76124],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Switch<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.<bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>library<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept>.<bpt id=\"p3\">*</bpt>switchname<ept id=\"p3\">*</ept>","source":"*Switch*.*library*.*switchname*"},{"pos":[76132,76188],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Changes to the task-based asynchronous pattern (TAP)<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>","source":"**Changes to the task-based asynchronous pattern (TAP)**"},{"content":"For apps that target the <ph id=\"ph1\">[!INCLUDE[net_v46](../../../includes/net-v46-md.md)]</ph>, <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task&gt;</ph> and <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task%601&gt;</ph> objects inherit the culture and UI culture of the calling thread.","pos":[76199,76421],"source":"For apps that target the [!INCLUDE[net_v46](../../../includes/net-v46-md.md)], <xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task> and <xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task%601> objects inherit the culture and UI culture of the calling thread."},{"content":"The behavior of apps that target previous versions of the .NET Framework, or that do not target a specific version of the .NET Framework, is unaffected.","pos":[76422,76574]},{"content":"For more information, see the \"Culture and task-based asynchronous operations\" section of the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo&gt;</ph> class topic.","pos":[76575,76721],"source":" For more information, see the \"Culture and task-based asynchronous operations\" sec